    Товч_агуулга_Англи:
      "This course surveys the main schools in the history of the development of economic thought, beginning with the Classical school and the works of Smith, Ricardo, J.S. Mill, Say, and others. It then reviews challenges to the classical school by Marx, Austrian and German historical schools, Marginalists, and subsequent key figures like Marshall, Walras and the Neoclassicalists. Economic thought associated with the early 20th century transitionalists are briefly addressed, including economists such as Wicksell, Schumpeter, Fisher, and others. Keynesian General Theory, in particular, areas of investment, interest rate theory and money demand is a concern. Post-1945 revisions of Keynes and Neoclassical economics in the form of early and late IS/LM analysis are reviewed, and its main challenges by Friedman (Monetarism), Lucas (Rational Expectations), neo Walras, non-Walras theorists, and post-Keynesian thought (UK and US). The course concludes with a consideration of efficient markets theory and contemporary macroeconomics (US). Throughout the course, economic theories will be examined considering the inter-relationships between theory, policies and conditions - including responses to the current global issues since 1990.",
