    Товч_агуулга_Англи:
      "Behavioural geography is an approach to human geography that attempts to understand human activity in space, place, and environment by studying it at the disaggregate level of analysis—at the level of an individual person. Behavioural geographers analyse data on the behaviour of individuals, recognising that individuals vary from each other. A key tenet of behavioural geography holds that models of human activity and interaction can be improved by incorporating more realistic assumptions about human behaviour. Behavioural geography maintains that human-environment relations are dynamic and bidirectional: The actions and mental states of individuals cause, and are caused by physical and social environments, within the context of ongoing and changing interactions",
